#             "definition": "The Bachelor of Secondary Education (BSEd) in Biology is an undergraduate academic degree program designed to prepare students for careers as secondary school teachers specializing in biology education.\n\nThe BSEd in Biology program combines education theory and pedagogy with specialized knowledge in biology to equip students with the skills and competencies needed to effectively teach biology to secondary school students. Students learn about fundamental concepts in biology, including cellular biology, genetics, ecology, evolution, physiology, and biodiversity.\n\nThroughout the program, students study a wide range of topics relevant to biology education, including curriculum development, instructional strategies, assessment methods, classroom management, educational psychology, and educational technology. They also gain practical teaching experience through supervised teaching practicums or internships in secondary school settings.\n\nThe curriculum typically includes a combination of core education courses, specialized courses in biology content and pedagogy, and field experiences in secondary school classrooms. Students may also have opportunities to explore specific areas of interest within biology through elective courses or research projects.\n\nA BSEd in Biology degree prepares students for licensure or certification as secondary school biology teachers. Graduates may pursue teaching positions in public or private secondary schools, including middle schools and high schools. They are qualified to teach biology-related subjects to students in grades 6-12, helping them develop a deep understanding of biological concepts and principles while fostering scientific inquiry and critical thinking skills.",
