#         "BACHELOR OF ELEMENTARY EDUCATION (SCIENCE AND MATHEMATICS)" : {
#             "definition": "The Bachelor of Elementary Education (BEEd) with a specialization in Science and Mathematics is an undergraduate academic degree program designed to prepare individuals for careers as elementary school teachers with expertise in teaching science and mathematics.\n\nThe BEEd program in Science and Mathematics focuses on equipping students with the knowledge, skills, and competencies necessary to effectively teach science and mathematics concepts to elementary school students. The curriculum integrates comprehensive coursework in science, mathematics, education, and pedagogy to provide students with a strong foundation in both content knowledge and teaching methodologies.\n\nStudents enrolled in the BEEd program undertake coursework covering various branches of science, such as biology, chemistry, physics, earth science, and environmental science. They explore scientific concepts, theories, and principles, as well as engage in hands-on laboratory activities and experiments. In addition, students study mathematics topics including arithmetic, algebra, geometry, measurement, statistics, and probability, with a focus on understanding mathematical concepts and problem-solving strategies.\n\nIn conjunction with science and mathematics content, students engage in education courses that address topics such as child development, educational psychology, curriculum development, instructional methods, classroom management, and assessment techniques. These courses provide students with the pedagogical knowledge and skills needed to design and deliver effective science and mathematics lessons, cater to diverse learning needs, and create a supportive and inclusive learning environment.\n\nA significant component of the BEEd program is the teaching practicum, where students gain practical experience by observing and teaching science and mathematics lessons in elementary school classrooms under the guidance of experienced mentor teachers and university faculty. This hands-on experience allows students to apply theoretical knowledge in real-world teaching settings, develop their teaching skills, and reflect on their practice.\n\nUpon completion of the program, graduates are prepared to pursue licensure or certification for teaching elementary education in their respective jurisdictions. They are equipped to inspire and engage elementary school students in the exploration of scientific and mathematical concepts, promote inquiry-based learning, critical thinking, and problem-solving skills, and foster a lifelong love for science, mathematics, and learning. Graduates may pursue careers as elementary school teachers, curriculum developers, educational consultants, or pursue further studies in education or related fields.",
#             "url": "https://www.msuiit.edu.ph/academics/colleges/ced/programs/sme/Form%205B%20BEED%20Sci%20and%20Math.pdf"
#         },
        
#         "BACHELOR OF SECONDARY EDUCATION (FILIPINO)" : {
#             "definition": "The Bachelor of Secondary Education (BSEd) with a specialization in Filipino is an undergraduate academic degree program designed to prepare individuals for careers as secondary school teachers specializing in teaching the Filipino language and literature.\n\nThe BSEd program in Filipino focuses on equipping students with the knowledge, skills, and competencies necessary to effectively teach Filipino language, literature, and culture to secondary school students. The curriculum integrates comprehensive coursework in Filipino language and literature, education, and pedagogy to provide students with a strong foundation in both content knowledge and teaching methodologies.\n\nStudents enrolled in the BSEd program undertake coursework covering various aspects of the Filipino language, including phonetics, grammar, syntax, semantics, morphology, and pragmatics. They also study Filipino literature, including poetry, prose, drama, and essays, from different historical periods and genres. Additionally, students explore Filipino culture, traditions, values, and identity through the study of Philippine history, society, and arts.\n\nIn conjunction with Filipino language and literature content, students engage in education courses that address topics such as educational psychology, curriculum development, instructional methods, classroom management, and assessment techniques. These courses provide students with the pedagogical knowledge and skills needed to design and deliver effective Filipino language and literature lessons, cater to diverse learning needs, and create a supportive and inclusive learning environment.\n\nA significant component of the BSEd program is the teaching practicum, where students gain practical experience by observing and teaching Filipino language and literature lessons in secondary school classrooms under the guidance of experienced mentor teachers and university faculty. This hands-on experience allows students to apply theoretical knowledge in real-world teaching settings, develop their teaching skills, and reflect on their practice.\n\nUpon completion of the program, graduates are prepared to pursue licensure or certification for teaching Filipino language and literature in secondary schools. They are equipped to inspire and engage secondary school students in the appreciation of the Filipino language, literature, and culture, promote language proficiency, critical thinking, and communication skills, and foster a deeper understanding and appreciation of Filipino identity and heritage. Graduates may pursue careers as secondary school Filipino teachers, language instructors, writers, editors, or pursue further studies in Filipino language and literature or related fields.",
#             "url": "https://www.msuiit.edu.ph/academics/colleges/ced/programs/pre/Form%205B%20BSEd%20Filipino.pdf"
#         },
        
#         "BACHELOR OF ELEMENTARY EDUCATION (LANGUAGE EDUCATION)" : {
#             "definition": "The Bachelor of Elementary Education (BEEd) with a specialization in Language Education is an undergraduate academic degree program designed to prepare individuals for careers as elementary school teachers with expertise in teaching language skills and literacy development.\n\nThe BEEd program in Language Education focuses on equipping students with the knowledge, skills, and competencies necessary to effectively teach language arts, literacy, and communication skills to elementary school students. The curriculum integrates comprehensive coursework in language education, education, and pedagogy to provide students with a strong foundation in both content knowledge and teaching methodologies.\n\nStudents enrolled in the BEEd program undertake coursework covering various aspects of language education, including language acquisition, linguistics, phonetics, phonology, morphology, syntax, semantics, pragmatics, literacy development, and language assessment. They explore effective instructional strategies for teaching reading, writing, speaking, listening, and language skills development across diverse populations of learners.\n\nIn conjunction with language education content, students engage in education courses that address topics such as child development, educational psychology, curriculum development, instructional methods, classroom management, and assessment techniques. These courses provide students with the pedagogical knowledge and skills needed to design and deliver effective language arts and literacy lessons, cater to diverse learning needs, and create a supportive and inclusive learning environment.\n\nA significant component of the BEEd program is the teaching practicum, where students gain practical experience by observing and teaching language arts and literacy lessons in elementary school classrooms under the guidance of experienced mentor teachers and university faculty. This hands-on experience allows students to apply theoretical knowledge in real-world teaching settings, develop their teaching skills, and reflect on their practice.\n\nUpon completion of the program, graduates are prepared to pursue licensure or certification for teaching elementary education with a specialization in language education in their respective jurisdictions. They are equipped to inspire and engage elementary school students in the development of language skills, promote literacy and communication skills, foster a love for reading and writing, and support language development across content areas. Graduates may pursue careers as elementary school language arts teachers, literacy specialists, reading interventionists, language tutors, or pursue further studies in language education or related fields.",
